Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=20
Happy Tuesday! Apologies for getting this one to you a day late. We had a w=
edding this weekend and an incredible Sixers overtime win on Sunday, and th=
is is one that I didn=E2=80=99t want to rush.=20
I=E2=80=99ve been thinking a lot about what happens when it becomes trivial=
ly easy to build software applications =E2=80=94 where value accrues, how a=
nd whether to build moats, and what to do about it =E2=80=94 and today=E2=
=80=99s essay is one draft of my thinking.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
 Small Applications, Growing Protocols
Brief dance in our hands,
Small Apps flicker, then depart,
Endless change expands.
=E2=80=93 ChatGPT
It=E2=80=99s easier than ever before to build great apps. It=E2=80=99s hard=
er than ever before to sustain them, to grow them into enduring companies.=
=C2=A0
Those two ideas are related, yin and yang.=C2=A0
Business models have not caught up to the potential of this new paradigm. S=
mall Apps create more potential value than they can capture; partnering up =
with protocols could fill the gap.
That easier to create equals harder to defend is not a revolutionary idea. =
It=E2=80=99s one I=E2=80=99ve been playing with for a while, since I wrote =
Shopify and the Hard Thing About Easy Things [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/c58a6897-646f-48b1-8b65-32b38928c95d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in August 2020: =E2=80=9CHere=E2=80=99s th=
e hard thing about easy things: if everyone can do something, there=E2=80=
=99s no advantage to doing it, but you still have to do it anyway just to k=
eep up.=E2=80=9D
That essay was about ecommerce specifically, but I wrote that the same patt=
ern was playing out across industries and verticals.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s happening in newsletters, where Substack gives writers an easy=
 way to try to become the next Ben Thompson. It=E2=80=99s happening in vide=
o games, where Epic Games is building the tools and literally giving them a=
way for free to expand the Total Addressable Market. It=E2=80=99s happening=
 in AI, where OpenAI is giving everyone GPT-3 to build on top of.
That last sentence has become more apparent in recent months as GPT-3 gave =
way to GPT-4. And it=E2=80=99s not just the GPT-wrappers, it=E2=80=99s the =
fact that AI makes it easier for anyone to build apps themselves, for everm=
ore niche use cases.=C2=A0
People like me like to write about whether or not these products have moats=
, whether they can stand the test of time. We=E2=80=99re already at the bac=
klash to the backlash on that subject:
Making something people want is good advice. Massive winners will be crowne=
d simply by making products that people love without worrying about growth =
hacking or moat digging. OpenAI CEO Sam Altman recently tweeted [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/61bd74ce-496e-41d3-95fb-2f47cb0905e4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] something to this effec=
t:
But at the same time, with everything moving so quickly, users are like kid=
s in a candy store, sampling everything, even paying for the sweetest, and =
then moving on to the next. Check out Lensa [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/f485bdb5-0329-4951-aec7-a6473083dea6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the first of this generation of AI apps to=
 take the App Store by storm:
