Small App Supernovae and Protocol Dyson Spheres
As things like Replit, AI, APIs, Urbit, and web3 protocols make it easier t=
o build apps, we=E2=80=99re seeing an explosion of Small Apps built for eve=
rmore specific use cases and user types.
Some Small Apps will be so small that they=E2=80=99ll be built by one perso=
n for one person, others will ride the zeitgeist to millions of users but f=
ade quickly. These are temporally small even if they get big for a time.=C2=
=A0
This is the kind of Small App I=E2=80=99m talking about here. They=E2=80=99=
re like supernovae. They burn brightly, explode, and fade away.=C2=A0
Competition (both direct and more generally for attention) and kid-in-candy=
-store users will make it brutally tough for Small Apps to turn into Big Ap=
p Companies, as is the case with Social Apps.=C2=A0
But a number of these Small Apps will be successful for a time. What if we =
could build Dyson Spheres around these Small App supernovae that capture an=
d harness their energy?=C2=A0
In a 1960 paper, Search for Artificial Stellar Sources of Infrared Radiatio=
n [ https://substack.com/redirect/13e44041-e4b7-4b95-832f-c244a89c70b2?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], physicist=
 Freeman Dyson proposed a system to capture all of the energy a star gives =
