Fat Protocols, Thin Applications
There is a popular framework, developed by Joel Monegro [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/5a08e56f-e222-4d14-abca-6b4edfbaaada?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] when he was at Union Square Ven=
tures, known as =E2=80=9CFat Protocols, Thin Applications.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
In 2016, before any of this stuff was obvious, Monegro wrote the first part=
: Fat Protocols [ https://substack.com/redirect/d3eaae49-c43e-4410-9430-2ae=
ae16dc9a7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ].
The general idea is that on the web, protocols like TCP/IP, HTML, and SMTP =
created a ton of value, but most of that value was captured by applications=
 like Facebook and Google. On blockchains, however, the value capture equat=
ion might be flipped: protocols could both create and capture most of the v=
alue driven by the apps built on them.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThere are two things about most blockchain-based protocols that ca=
use this to happen,=E2=80=9D he wrote. =E2=80=9CThe first is the shared dat=
a layer, and the second is the introduction cryptographic =E2=80=98access=
=E2=80=99 token with some speculative value.=E2=80=9D
In a 2020 follow-up, written from his own fund, Placeholder, Monegro covere=
d the other side of the equation: Thin Applications [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/e4061f2e-f248-45fa-a926-b80168a97719?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
In it, he highlighted the benefits and drawbacks of building applications o=
n top of crypto protocols. Essentially, he argued that while a =E2=80=9Ccry=
ptoservices architecture is great for startups=E2=80=9D because they can bu=
ild quickly, cheaply, and with a high level of capital efficiency, =E2=80=
=9Cwheat seems unclear to many is how exactly they can create long-term bus=
iness value and defensibility when everything is open.=E2=80=9D
This setup is great for users and addresses many of our gripes with the web=
=2E But it raises new questions about d=
efensibility at the application layer.=
 How do you create long-term business value and defensibility when everythi=
ng is open and competitors can so easily substitute each other?=C2=A0
La plus =C3=A7a change=E2=80=A6 This debate around long-term business value=
 and defensibility in the face of tremendous competition is the same one ra=
ging today if you swap out web3 protocols for AI APIs.=C2=A0
At the end of the piece, Monegro laid out three ways that applications migh=
t create long-term value and defensibility:=C2=A0
Building a cost moat: centralizing costs and externalities unaccounted for =
by the protocols.
Vertical integration: successful applications may amass enough users to =E2=
=80=9Cbecome their own supply=E2=80=9D.
User-staking: leveraging tokens to distribute value and upside to users.
Three years later, a number of applications have used these three strategie=
s to varying degrees of success, but the fact remains that most value has b=
een captured by the protocols. You need to scroll down to #20 on CoinMarket=
Cap=E2=80=99s list of top coins by market cap to find an application token =
=E2=80=93 Bitfinex=E2=80=99s UNUS SED LEO token =E2=80=93 and to #22 to get=
 to an application you=E2=80=99ve heard of: Uniswap. Even Uniswap=E2=80=99s=
 UNI token is tied to the protocol and not the Uniswap app, but it=E2=80=99=
s the closest we come in the top 30.=C2=A0
It seems as if the debate is mostly settled: Gravity pulls value down to th=
e protocol. Fat protocols, thin applications.
Instead of trying to fight gravity by creating defensibility and long-term =
business value, what if protocols and applications intentionally designed t=
hemselves around the idea that Small Apps can=E2=80=99t expect to create de=
fensibility and long-term business value? What if they worked with gravity?=
