line;">Crypto Tokens</a><span> </span></em><span>back in 2017 (there&#8217;=
s always a Chris Dixon essay).&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>What&#8217;s=
 different here is that </span><strong>the applications themselves should b=
e centralized and should not issue their own tokens</strong><span>. Small A=
pps should use the protocol&#8217;s token and push more value to the protoc=
ol, where most of the value is bound to accrue anyway. They recognize their=
 ephemerality and are incentivized to make the protocol itself successful.&=
#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 2=
6px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>They should do everything that they would n=
ormally do to build the most compelling apps possible, they&#8217;d essenti=
ally just </span><strong>swap out their database for the protocol&#8217;s</=
strong><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>That&#8217;s a big ask to make on =
the surface. Owning users and data is exactly how Facebook got so big! Agai=
n, this is not for everyone. The Go For It camp should Go For It. But for m=
ost Small Apps, if you&#8217;re able to admit that you&#8217;re not going t=
o be Facebook, I think this trade has a deeply positive expected value. You=
